content: Had a glitch at the end whete peck vanished and i couldnt finish, bur i replayed it 2 more times....i forgot tp sit in a chsir and grab a spring my second playthrough. Near the end of the game, I'm required to retrieve the bird, close to a machine. I'm on a phone, I have large fingers, I am not using a computer mouse. Everytime I try to grab the bird, the game thinks I'm pressing the machine. I literally cannot complete the game because the select options for the bird and the machine are directly next to each other. I looked it up, and other people are able to click the bird just fine on pc. Besides that, the game is absolutely stellar, imaginative, and fun!

You are gifted. I am drunk playing this. But I really want to tell you devs and artists how much I appreciate this game. You are Demi God's and deserve love and credit for great work and creativity. You got one soul here faaaar away sending you cosmic thanks!

A game that requires a walkthrough to avoid game-ending choices, is not a good game. While aesthetics are GORGEOUS, they do not make up for the flaws that brick this game.

Great artwork in a strange world with a fun story. Phenomenal story, characters and graphics. The world-building is beyond most games out there. It's a shame about the bugs: i.e. 1) when there are animations playing in the scene, you have to long-press and slide to interact with stuff, 2) the bottom drawer overlaps with the scene objects and the flute, 3) the birdseed can 'disappear' at the beginning and you have to start the game over, 4) minimizing the game makes it reboot every time, 5) and the nose flute is flaky and frustrating. The programmer should really have tried harder. Even with those bugs, I still have to give it 5 stars for how good the rest of it was. I felt connected to the characters. Some of the puzzles were impossible to figure out, so it's good there are hints in-game. I wish it were more polished.

This was just what I have been searching for! When I was younger, I played a games on the computer called "Day of the Tentacle", "Goblin Quest" and "Sam and Max"; which were all 2d point and click adventure with a brilliantly unique storyline, lovable characters, witty dialogue options, and creative problem solving solutions. I have not been able to find anything like that since and this game brought me back to my childhood. Amazing! Please make more!!!

Some solutions come from way outside the box, but the UHS-like hint system keeps you playing. The art style and narrative are simple, but very engaging and the voice acting is just right. This game is a big hurrah to the genre and if you consider yourself a fan of point & click, you owe it to yourself to play it.

This game had a strong plot which held my interest. I couldnt wait to get to the end to find out what happens. I had zero bugs or glitches as others have reported. Problem solving in the first couple of levels was fun but I found subsequent levels incredibly frustrating because many problems are completely illogical. There wasn't any reasonable or intuitive way to solve the puzzles, it becomes mindless trial and error. The solution to some problems are so unintuitive that I felt I was wasting my time trying to think them through and I fully relied on the hints for more than half of the game. I also found it frustrating to backtrack between scenes. Rather than having a progressive flow through rooms or scenes, you have to backtrack to pick something up - not because you missed it but because something random such as a conversation triggers eg. A wall to crumble which creates dust you need to return to retrieve. For those interested, this game does not pass the bechedel test. I found this mildly annoying, but noticable enough to add to my review. + The character Laura is cool but "bitchy".. hmmm. I rated 3/5 for plot interest and novelty but it is frankly quite frustrating to play because it is so illogical. Would not have purchased had I known this in advance.

If adventure games are either entertaining or fun, this one is highly entertaining and moderately fun.   Characters are well drawn, the animated sci-fi environment immersive, and the plot is original.  Gameplay is a mix of collect and use objects, hidden objects, and plot -based puzzles.  The cut scenes are fun to watch, and the game lasts a long time.  I had some trouble manipulating objects on a small screen.  Some puzzles are contrived and difficult, but the help function is excellent.

The puzzles range from fairly easy to fiendishly hard. Fortunately, the help system is well designed to give you clues at the level you need. The game can be a little fiddly on a small screen, but the graphics and animations are superb. It's not a game to finish in a single evening (unless you have nothing to do for several hours), but its variation and occasional humour keep it fresh and interesting.

The touch mechanics for the phone version of this game are at times frustrating but never that big of a deal. I really liked this game.

Sometimes I miss having more logical structure but the struggle was worth it. Both of the main  characters annoyed me, at times, but the overall effect was marvelous. Plus, I love to support hand drawn pictures . . . jobs for starving artists, and art for me to appreciate for the hard work and retro nostalgia.

This is for version 1.6 on the Google Nexus 7 tablet.  "The Inner World" would be a fantastic game, but the bugs make it so frustrating to play that I almost quit.  The minor ones are that the voices are are sometimes out of sync or they just cut out.  There were also a few animation errors.   The worst problems by far, however, were the issues with the interface.  Very frequently, clickable areas were misaligned, making it very difficult to use the tools or click on the areas to interact with them  Alignment also presented a problem when building tools: parts that were supposed to fit together didn't interact on the first try.  Sometimes, tool icons would get stuck behind other tool icons. The dots indicating the clickable areas only appeared if I dragged a tool icon onto the screen, which was cumbersome.  There should be a switch of some sort that will toggle the clickable areas on and off.   These problems render the game almost unplayable.  This is a shame because it's such a wonderfully written game.  That being said, I wouldn't pay for another game from this studio

Quite amusing and not too difficult overall, with some quite frustratingly tricky parts to keep you thinking. In all, it took nearly four hours for me to complete this game, which I'm not entirely sure was worth the price, but I enjoyed the structure and gameplay.  I didn't love the way the principal character was drawn; it looks creepy. And his voice is even creepier. In fact, so many of the other parts are so poorly voice-acted that I found it a great improvement to turn off the voice and just read the subtitles. Dialogues are frequently too drawn-out and puns tend to fall a little flat (but that might be in part due to translation issues).  That aside, the game also crashes far too often. This is not too bad because it auto-saves after (almost) every significant progression.  I bought this game hoping to find something like Discworld or Monkey Island. It falls short of that lofty goal, and unlike those games I don't think I will go back and play this one again, but it has done all right in keeping me amused for a day.

Lovely game but only just playable, if I hadn't spent money on it I would have given up after about 20mins. How did this ever get released? there are so many different types of problems. Crashing, hotspots that don't click, dragging objects sometimes leave them in midair, z-order problems, text and speech not matching, having to wait while nothing happens, not to mention the huge long times waiting for stuff to load when moving between rooms. When you need to move back and forth between locations in a game, it is not on to have to wait thirty seconds. Enjoyed the game, hated the experience, wish I had asked for a refund!
